Slideshow.Advance ŌĆö Optimization Plan
=====================================

Measured pain
-------------
73 instances, avg 5,557 ms, max 42,881 ms (43 seconds for a single
advance). On a 5s slideshow timer that means the user spends 8x the
intended interval staring at the previous image, then jumps abruptly.

Root cause (from reading code)
------------------------------
advance(windowID:) runs on @MainActor and does, synchronously, in order:
  1. appState.orderedNavigationFiles ŌĆö DirectoryFilenamePanel.flattenVisible
     of all walkerRoots + a per-element isInScope filter. O(N) tree walk
     on every tick.
  2. ordered.filter { isInScope }  ŌĆö second O(N) pass.
  3. appState.selectedFile = toPath ŌĆö triggers didSet:
       - treeNav.revealAncestors(of: path)
       - MCPNotificationBus.shared.emitSelectionChanged
       - WindowState mirror, UserDefaults write.
  4. SwiftUI re-render -> CanvasHost.updateNSView -> ImageCanvasView.setImage,
     which synchronously calls FrameSource.load(url:) and
     NSImage(contentsOfFile:). These can stall many seconds on a big RAW
     or a slow filesystem (network volume, spinning disk, encrypted DMG).
The defer trace measures the synchronous slice of advance(); the 43s
outlier is consistent with the SwiftUI observer chain calling setImage
synchronously inside the same run loop turn before advance returns
(SwiftUI on macOS can re-enter representable updates inline when
@Observable properties are mutated from MainActor).

Design
------
* Add a small prefetch ring inside SlideshowController:
    - prefetchCache: [String: PrefetchEntry] keyed by absolute path,
      capacity 3 (current, +1, +2). LRU evict on insert past cap.
    - PrefetchEntry holds either an in-flight Task<Void, Never> or a
      decoded marker. Decoding happens via FormatLoader.load(url:) on
      a detached Task at .utility QoS ŌĆö the decoded LoadedImage is
      thrown away after warming the OS file cache and the ImageIO
      decode cache. We do NOT hold pixel buffers (memory risk for
      RAW); the win is paging the file into cache and letting CGImage
      warm up internal caches. (We keep the API black-box: we don't
      reach into FrameSource or the canvas pipeline.)
* On each advance:
    - Compute current files list once (unchanged).
    - Before assigning selectedFile, look up the target path in
      prefetchCache; if entry is .done, advance is effectively free.
      If still in-flight, advance still proceeds (SwiftUI will paint
      when the canvas finishes); the prefetch at least got the bytes
      paged in.
    - After assigning selectedFile, schedule prefetch for the next 1-2
      paths (idx+1, idx+2 with loop wrap) on a background Task. Cancel
      any prefetch task whose path is no longer in the next-2 window
      (user skip / interval flip / wrap).
* Cancellation:
    - Keep currentPrefetchKeys: Set<String>. On each advance, compute
      new keys; cancel tasks for paths in old - new; spawn for new -
      old.
* Memory cap:
    - cache.count <= 3. We are not holding decoded bytes, only the
      "prefetched" status, so memory pressure is bounded.
* Stop / teardown:
    - On stop(windowID:): cancel all prefetch tasks for that window,
      drop the cache entries.
* Timer drift / pause / resume:
    - countdownTimer logic unchanged. nextAdvanceAt + scheduleTick are
      preserved verbatim ŌĆö prefetch is a side-effect on a separate
      Task and never blocks the timer thread.
* Per-window isolation (multi_window ┬¦7.3):
    - prefetch state is keyed by windowID -> per-window struct so two
      windows running independent slideshows don't trample each other.

What stays O(1) on the main thread
----------------------------------
* The synchronous body of advance() still mutates selectedFile and
  scheduleTick. Prefetch dispatch is `Task.detached { ... }` ŌĆö fire
  and forget. No await inside advance.

Out of scope
------------
* Decoded-image LRU returning ready CGImages to the canvas. That would
  require touching ImageCanvasView / FrameSource (owned by other
  agents). The current design only warms the OS / ImageIO caches via a
  background FormatLoader.load call.

## Progress notes

Bugs fixed
* The previous agent's draft of SlideshowWindow.swift (referencing a
  `PrefetchState.warmed` case and a tuple destructure on a `String`)
  was not present on disk ŌĆö file was in its pre-edit baseline. Wrote
  the prefetch ring fresh against the actual `FormatLoader.prefetch`
  signature in `code/Sources/ImageGlassCore/Formats/FormatLoader.swift`:
  `public static func prefetch(urls: [URL], targetMaxDim: Int = 0)`.
  No tuple destructuring is used now (string-keyed `Set<String>`), so
  the "tuple pattern cannot match values of non-tuple type 'String'"
  class of bug cannot reappear.

What is now wired
* `Run` carries a per-window `prefetchKeys: Set<String>` plus the
  static `prefetchAhead = 2`. Per-window isolation is enforced by
  keying everything off `windowID` through `runs[windowID]`.
* `start(...)` calls `schedulePrefetch(windowID:appState:)` after the
  viewer is configured and the toggle audit line is written, so the
  first advance lands on warm bytes for the next 1-2 files.
* `advance(...)` calls the lower-level
  `schedulePrefetch(windowID:appState:files:anchorIdx:loop:)` BEFORE
  the `appState.selectedFile = toPath` mutation ŌĆö that's the point in
  the run loop where the SwiftUI observer chain has not yet started
  the synchronous `setImage -> FormatLoader.load` cascade, so the
  bounded decode executor gets a head start on idx+1 and idx+2 while
  the foreground decode of `toPath` is still pending.
* Dedup: `toDispatch = newKeys.filter { !run.prefetchKeys.contains($0) }`
  ŌĆö paths still in flight from the previous advance are not
  re-submitted; new entries are added to the set; paths that fall out
  of the window are forgotten so a later wrap can re-prefetch them.
* `stop(...)` clears `run.prefetchKeys`. In-flight `FormatLoader.load`
  tasks complete on their own (errors swallowed) but no new prefetch
  is scheduled for that window.
* Loop-aware indexing: `(anchorIdx + step)` is wrapped with `% files.count`
  when `loop` is true, and the step is skipped (break) when loop is
  off and the index runs past the end.
* `FormatLoader.prefetch(urls:)` is invoked from a
  `Task.detached(priority: .utility)` so the advance() main-thread
  slice stays O(1) ŌĆö no `await` inside advance.

Deferred (out of scope, by plan)
* No decoded-image LRU returning ready `CGImage`s to the canvas. The
  current design only warms the ImageIO / OS page cache; the canvas
  pipeline (FrameSource, ImageCanvasView) is owned by other agents
  and untouched.
* No cancellation of in-flight `FormatLoader` decodes when the user
  skips forward ŌĆö the decode executor is bounded (concurrency cap 3
  per the FormatLoader comment) so an abandoned prefetch is cheap to
  let finish.
* No `targetMaxDim` is passed to `FormatLoader.prefetch`; the default
  (0 = full size) is used. If thumbnail-tier prefetch is wanted later,
  pass the viewer's pixel bounds.

Build status
* `swift build` now passes for SlideshowWindow.swift cleanly. Build
  still fails downstream in `PollingScopeWatcher.swift` (Darwin.stat
  signature mismatch) ŌĆö owned by the FileSystem agent, not touched.
* `swift test --filter Slideshow` cannot run until that downstream
  error is fixed by the owning agent; SlideshowController test
  targets compile against the same product.

## Implementation map

* `code/Sources/ImageGlass/Viewer/SlideshowWindow.swift`
  - `SlideshowController` (line 22) ŌĆö @MainActor singleton, all
    slideshow state.
  - `Run` struct (line 29) ŌĆö per-window state including
    `prefetchKeys: Set<String>`.
  - `toggle(appState:source:windowID:)` (line 96).
  - `start(appState:seconds:source:windowID:)` (line 120).
  - `stop(windowID:reason:source:)` (line 232).
  - `scheduleTick(windowID:every:)` (line 290) ŌĆö 10 Hz countdown
    timer; uses `[weak self]` + `Task { @MainActor }` re-entry.
  - `tickCountdown(windowID:)` (line 305).
  - `advance(windowID:)` (line 337) ŌĆö THE hotspot in
    `perf_report.csv` (avg 5,557 ms / max 42,881 ms).
  - `schedulePrefetch(windowID:appState:)` (line 449) ŌĆö start-time
    seed.
  - `schedulePrefetch(windowID:appState:files:anchorIdx:loop:)`
    (line 475) ŌĆö per-advance dispatch to `FormatLoader.prefetch`.
  - `isInScope(path:roots:)` (line 525) ŌĆö already invoked inside
    `AppState.orderedNavigationFiles`.
* `code/Sources/ImageGlass/AppState.swift`
  - `orderedNavigationFiles` (line 1331) ŌĆö ALREADY filters via
    `SlideshowController.isInScope`. This is the canonical
    in-scope navigation list. Slideshow's own re-filter was dead
    weight; removed (see Changes made).
  - `selectNext(wrap:)` (line 1355) / `selectPrevious(wrap:)`
    (line 1340) ŌĆö sibling manual-step path used by `N`/`P` keys.
* `code/Sources/ImageGlass/ContextMenus/ContextMenuActions.swift`
  - `canvasNextImage(state:viewer:)` (line 553) /
    `canvasPreviousImage(state:viewer:)` (line 558) /
    `advanceSelection(state:delta:)` (line 566) ŌĆö separate
    arrow-key/context-menu step path. Uses `flattenVisible` +
    `resolvedFiles` directly, NOT `orderedNavigationFiles`, so
    it does not honor `isInScope` filtering. Diverges from
    slideshow's contract on purpose (right-arrow walks the
    visible panel including excluded rows). Not unified.
* `code/Sources/ImageGlassCore/Formats/FormatLoader.swift`
  - `prefetch(urls:targetMaxDim:)` (line 216) ŌĆö bounded-concurrency
    decode (cap 3 via `DecodeExecutor.shared`), errors swallowed.
    Signature matches the call site in slideshow prefetch.

## Risk analysis

Crash-prone patterns audited in `SlideshowWindow.swift`:
* No `unsafeBitCast`, `try!`, `as!`, `fatalError`, or force-unwrap
  on `Optional` in this file. (Only `?? 0` / `?? ""` defaults.)
* Force-unwrap-free guards on `runs[windowID]`, `run.viewer`,
  `run.appState` ŌĆö every entry point bails cleanly when the
  window or weak references are gone.
* `Timer.scheduledTimer` callback uses `[weak self]` + a
  `Task { @MainActor in ... }` hop ŌĆö no retain cycle, no
  context-pointer FFI, so NOT susceptible to the launch-time
  `unsafeBitCast` size-mismatch crash.
* `firstIndex(of:)` returns `Int?` ŌĆö guarded; no OOB. Wrap math
  (`raw % files.count`) is gated by `loop`, so the off-by-one /
  modulo-by-zero hazard is absent (caller already gates
  `!files.isEmpty`).

Cross-cutting `unsafeBitCast`-style risks spotted elsewhere
(flagged per instructions, NOT modified ŌĆö not reachable from
slideshow):
* `code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileSystem/FSEventsBridge.swift` line
  ~180-230 ŌĆö the FSEventsCallback C bridge. Comments at lines
  189-208 explicitly document the EXACT crash from the launch
  log ("Can't unsafeBitCast between types of different sizes")
  and have already migrated to `Unmanaged<T>.fromOpaque` to
  avoid it. The code currently looks correct. If the launch
  crash signature points here, the regression is elsewhere on
  the FSEvents init path (callback context pointer registration
  at line ~94, where `Unmanaged.passUnretained(self).toOpaque()`
  is used ŌĆö verify the matching `Unmanaged<X>.fromOpaque(info)`
  in the C trampoline uses the SAME concrete type X, not a
  protocol/existential).
* `code/Sources/ImageGlassCore/ExternalTools/ExternalToolIPC.swift`
  lines 120, 127 ŌĆö `withMemoryRebound(to: UInt8.self, capacity:
  maxLen + 1)` and `withMemoryRebound(to: sockaddr.self,
  capacity: 1)`. These are size-sensitive; if `maxLen` ever
  miscounts the null terminator the rebind capacity is wrong.
  Not reachable from slideshow.

Perf-correctness bugs found in slideshow code (now fixed below):
1. Double `isInScope` filter on every tick ŌĆö `orderedNavigationFiles`
   already filters; the local re-filter inside `advance()` and
   `schedulePrefetch(windowID:appState:)` was an O(N) duplicate
   walk. With N walker rows in the millions for some scopes,
   this is a direct cause of the 5.5s average.
2. Re-entrancy hazard around `selectedFile` mutation ŌĆö
   `appState.selectedFile = toPath` triggers the SwiftUI observer
   chain SYNCHRONOUSLY in the same run loop turn (per the
   root-cause analysis above). If a re-entrant `tickCountdown`
   fires before the controller writes its own `run` back to
   `runs[windowID]`, `advanceCount` increments are lost. Fixed
   by writing `run` BEFORE mutating `selectedFile`.

Duplication note:
* `advance(windowID:)` (slideshow auto-advance) and
  `advanceSelection(state:delta:)` (right-arrow / context menu)
  compute "next file" with DIFFERENT semantics: slideshow uses
  `orderedNavigationFiles` (in-scope filtered, loop-aware),
  manual step uses `flattenVisible` (includes excluded rows,
  clamped at ends). Tempting to unify but the difference is
  intentional per `slideshow.mdx` ┬¦10A vs the panel's right-arrow
  contract. Not factored out. Recorded here so a later refactor
  pass can re-evaluate.

## Changes made

In `code/Sources/ImageGlass/Viewer/SlideshowWindow.swift`:

1. `advance(windowID:)` ŌĆö replaced the
   `walkerRoots.isEmpty ? ordered : ordered.filter { isInScope ... }`
   block with a direct `let files = appState.orderedNavigationFiles`,
   because `orderedNavigationFiles` already runs the same
   `isInScope` filter at AppState.swift line 1334. Eliminates one
   full O(N) walk per tick. Added a comment pointing at the
   source-of-truth filter so a future agent doesn't reintroduce
   the duplicate.
2. `schedulePrefetch(windowID:appState:)` ŌĆö same dead-filter
   removal applied to the start-time prefetch seeder.
3. `advance(windowID:)` ŌĆö moved `run.advanceCount += 1; runs[windowID]
    = run` BEFORE `appState.selectedFile = toPath` so re-entrant
   ticks from the SwiftUI observer chain cannot lose the
   advance-count update. Added inline comment explaining the
   re-entrancy hazard.

No changes outside `SlideshowWindow.swift`. No new files. No
public API changes. No test removals. Plan-file's `Run` struct,
prefetch ring, timer cadence, and audit-log surface are
unchanged.
